text: I'll admit it, I'm not the hugest fan of Christopher Nolan. I appreciate him tremendously and I really enjoyed a couple of his flicks (like some of his Batman flick and Inception specifically). I haven't seen everything but his more recent stuff I've seen from him like Interstellar and Dunkirk have been mediocre at best. I hate to say this but his writing and dialogue is not for me. This one, based on the trailer alone, has got me generally excited. It definitely looks and feels like a Nolan flick but something about this has intrigued me more than his other flicks. Maybe it's just some of the eccentric performances that are currently being showcased here like Washington, Pattinson and Branagh or the fascinating way the flick seems to be executing it's premise that's creative and action-packed but with a generally smart mind to it that doesn't come across as pretentious (ala Inception).

text: July 17 2020? Yeah okay. I'll believe it when I see it. Also, since it's getting mentioned a lot... NASA has NOT found evidence of a parallel universe where time goes backwards. What a related observatory in Antarctica did find were some neutrinos behaving in unexplained ways. The parallel universe idea is one of several hypotheses to explain this. The hypothesis most widely being looked at by scientists is that they need to study Antarctica's ice more. The parallel universe idea's a bit more fringe. But that apparently makes better headlines than "NASA has found evidence that we know less about Antarctic ice than previously thought" (although I personally want to read *that* article, instead).

Explanation about timelines and link with parallel universe: In short, there are multiple timelines in this universe ( not like 100 or 1000 or 10000 timelines) but, for smallest unit of time , i.e. less than millisecpnd, or like nanoseconds. For each nanosecond , there is a timeline fixated. This timeline works just in parallel with other infinite number of timelines.   What Tenet's Inversion might actually be? In other movies, Time travel is simply shown as Past present and future. But this Inversion thing, really thrills me up . It might be that the user or time traveller can simply jump from one timeline to another timeline. He in the timeline, where he is originally from, will have noone of the user's existence ( Google for better understanding).  Limitation of This Timeline jumps: Butterfly effect. text: I said it from the first trailer on... This is Nolan taking his usual bit from Kubrick, using spectral reverses in this case and a convoluted plot, which will only make sense once viewed in whole. Still, I'm waiting for the day that Nolan uses all that money, but especially his FREEDOM to make a film without boundaries and full of ambiguities. I know its impossible to be Kubrick but he can be a master filmmaker when he decides. I enjoy all of his work. I just want more. Tarantino may not have made a Masterpiece with 'OUATIH' but watching him create a film with zero f**ks about studio execs was still great to see. I want that from Nolan. 'Dunkirk' was close but not daring enough. It didnt have you asking questions when leaving the theater. I'm hoping we finally get that with 'Tenet' but I doubt it.

text: the concept of tenet is explained in its name "tenet". Tenet is an example of a palindrome which means the word is still the same as reading it "backwards". In other words, in the shooting range, the bullet travels backwards. The person with the gun perceives the time forward while the object (the rock) perceives the time backward. It still leads to the "same" outcome that the bullet exists.

text: For those that need an explanation: Time Inversion is when events have effects before cause. For example, when Robert asks, "What the hell happened here?" and John replies, "It hasn't happened yet." It's because the bullet holes exist w/o the gun being shot at the glass. So when you see him fighting that soldier, the soldier isn't shooting bullets at John. The bullets are bouncing off the window back into the bullet chamber. Same thing when he shoots the bullet at the rock. Those bullets have already been shot at the rock. So when he pulls the trigger, the bullets are going off the rock back into the bullet chamber. He's "catching the bullet." Time travel is going back to when events haven't happened. Time inversion is when events have happened but the cause comes after. So usually it's cause and effect. Inversion is effect then cause. And events around the characters are happening backwards while everything else continues to move foward. In time travel, everything is moved backwards.

text: I noticed a pattern in the release of his movies. They're grouped into trilogies, though only one is official. The grounded trilogy: Memento Insomnia Prestige  The superhero trilogy: Batman Begins The Dark Knight The Dark Knight Rises  The science fiction trilogy: Inception Interstellar Tenet  Dunkirk is the start of the most recent one. We shall see. Anyway, stay with me.  So, Nolan makes two movies of a trilogy, and then makes the first movie of the next one just to announce what is next before finally making the third movie and concluding the trilogy. Then he proceeds to do the same with the new trilogy and so on. He made Memento and Insomnia, both  grounded films filled with mystery. Then he started his superhero trilogy with Batman Begins before releasing Prestige that is also a grounded movie filled with mystery. Then he proceeded to continue his superhero trilogy with The Dark Knight. Then he made Inception, the first movie of his blockbuster sci-fi trilogy. Then he could conclude his superhero trilogy with The Dark Knight Rises. He proceeded with his sci-fi trilogy by releasing Interstellar. Then he started the fourth trilogy with Dunkirk, which promises to be an action packed visual marvel with minimal dialogue. Now when he's started that, he has come back to his sci-fi trilogy to wrap it up with Tenet. I also noticed that he always makes the first and third movie very similar to give us a sense of closure.  Memento and Prestige are both non-linear and confusing, unlike a more clear Insomnia. Batman Begins and TDKR both feature The League of Shadows and high stakes action, unlike the more philosophical TDK. Now, I notice that Inception and Tenet could actually be related and are similar from the looks of it. Interstellar is way more big and epic.

text: The simple explanation for the time cone is that the speed of light is 300,000 kilometers per second, and when the distance between two objects is greater than that, the object we see is no longer the object itself, but its image at the time. For example, a star may have disappeared years ago, but it will take years for light to travel until we can feel its disappearance. Assuming that the sun ceases to shine, this event will have no effect on earth at this moment, and we can only be affected by this event in the absolute past five minutes later, when earth is within the future light cone of the event. The movie may use this logic, an event will generate a future light cone, the event is approaching us at the speed of light, its physical effects are completely unpredictable before arrival, because we do not find the event happening, we are still outside the future light cone of the event. The protagonist himself may have some ability, or borrow some ability, to perceive and enter the future light cone, to make some kind of change before events affect the present.

text: i don't know if it's just me... or Why no one is talking about this.. the word "Tenet" is actually "TEN" where "N" is common and "TE" is coming out from left and right sides thus, making "TEN-TEN" in my mind's visual array or as i would like to interpret it commonly as " TENET" as  the inversion of the other half makes in our mind in order to read "TEN-TEN" - where "N" common- as "TENET" thus, justifying "Time inversion" with inversion of letters. Some of you may think whats "Time" got to with the word "TEN-TEN" well a lot actually, All the wrist watches are initially set "Time" as "10:10" paying homage to the inventor of the watch a dutch scientist and mathematician, Christiaan Huygens, who invented the first pendulum clock. the time "10:10" was his eureka moment. so that's why all the dials of wrist watch are set as "10:10" thus the idea in the name of the movie with respects to "Time inversion" also Lincoln was shot at "10:15" five minutes after he sat down..yes, if he decided to walk away before the watch hit "10:10" would be alive..thus "Time Inversion"  Christopher Nolan is genius!!
